          Everything might be=C2=A0securities fraudWe  talked in February a=
bout a securities-fraud lawsuit against Goldman Sachs Group Inc. that was g=
oing all the way to the=C2=A0Supreme Court. The issue is that, before the 2=
008 global financial crisis, Goldman had gone around saying things like =E2=
=80=9Cour clients=E2=80=99 interests always come first=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=
=9Cintegrity and honesty are at the heart of our business.=E2=80=9D Then th=
e global financial crisis occurred, and:=09It came out that maybe Goldman=
=E2=80=99s clients=E2=80=99 interests sometimes came second, and maybe inte=
grity and honesty were sometimes not quite at the=C2=A0heart=C2=A0of its bu=
siness[1]; and=09Goldman=E2=80=99s stock price went down.Why did the stock =
price go down? Well, I mean, there=C2=A0was=C2=A0a global financial crisis.=
 That was bad, for earnings and such. Also, though,=C2=A0Goldman got in (le=
gal, political, public-relations) trouble for some of the specific instance=
s in which its clients=E2=80=99 interests arguably came second; for instanc=
e, famously, it paid a big fine for doing some bad=C2=A0stuff with a mortga=
ge security called Abacus.=C2=A0There is perhaps a third, less specific rea=
son. Perhaps in 2007, investors read in Goldman=E2=80=99s disclosures that=
=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cour clients=E2=80=99 interests always come first=E2=80=9D an=
d =E2=80=9Cintegrity and honesty are at the heart of our business,=E2=80=9D=
 and they thought: =E2=80=9CYes, it is good that Goldman has integrity and =
puts its clients=E2=80=99 interests first, that is valuable for its busines=
s, we will buy the stock.=E2=80=9D In 2009, after Abacus and so forth, inve=
stors thought =E2=80=9Calas, no, Goldman does not have integrity and does n=
ot put its clients=E2=80=99 interests first, we are disappointed, we will s=
ell the stock.=E2=80=9D In other words, perhaps investors=C2=A0ascribed val=
ue=C2=A0to Goldman=E2=80=99s statements about integrity and honesty, and th=
en when they found out that those statements were not true that value went =
away and the stock went down.Are you laughing? A little, right? Investors m=
ainly ascribed value to Goldman=E2=80=99s income stream, and the stock main=
ly went down due to Goldman losing money. But of course,=C2=A0at some margi=
n integrity is valuable, and maybe investors thought Goldman had like 100 u=
nits of integrity (after reading their disclosures) but revised that estima=
te down to 80 units (after reading the Abacus settlement), and each unit of=
 integrity was worth a dollar to the stock price and so forth.If you believ=
e this theory, then it was=C2=A0securities fraud=C2=A0for Goldman to talk a=
 lot about having a lot of integrity and honestly when in fact it secretly =
knew that it had less integrity and honesty. Goldman was cooking the integr=
ity-and-honesty books. Each quarter the results came in and the business de=
livered only 80 units of honesty and integrity, but the market was demandin=
g 100 units, so Goldman=E2=80=99s executives fudged the numbers and reporte=
d a full supply of honesty and integrity. =E2=80=9COur clients=E2=80=99 int=
erests came first on 73 out of 91 days this quarter,=E2=80=9D the assistant=
 treasurer reported, and the chief financial officer was like =E2=80=9Cthat=
=E2=80=99s not good enough, we need to report that our clients=E2=80=99 int=
erests=C2=A0always=C2=A0came first, find a way to make it happen!=E2=80=9DA=
nyway this went to the Supreme Court and there were some arguments about th=
e theory=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0which I talk about a lot around here =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0that =E2=80=9Ceverything is securities fraud.=E2=80=9D If companies s=
ay vague nice things about themselves =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cwe have a cod=
e of ethics,=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9Cthe client comes first,=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9Cwe=
 have a culture of risk management,=E2=80=9D etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0and then a=
 bad thing happens, a shareholder will sue, arguing that the vague nice sta=
tements were lies=C2=A0that deceived investors and pumped up the stock, and=
 that when the bad thing happened the truth was revealed and the stock drop=
ped. When we  talked about it in February, I quoted some amicus curiae brie=
fs like this one[2]:Frequently, event-driven claims allege that generic or =
aspirational statements, similar to ones made by virtually every public com=
pany, maintained inflation in a company=E2=80=99s stock price. Allegations =
of wrongdoing nearly always conflict, at some level of generality, with a c=
ompany=E2=80=99s code of conduct or other statements of corporate policy. S=
o it is not difficult for plaintiffs to allege that negative reporting or d=
isclosures =E2=80=9Ccorrected=E2=80=9D a prior, generic policy statement (e=
.g., =E2=80=9CWe strive to comply with all applicable laws.=E2=80=9D). The =
result is that just about any corporate controversy that coincides with a d=
rop in stock price can be re-characterized as a securities fraud. Examples =
abound. COVID-19 exposure on cruise ships, wildfires, data breaches, and se=
xual-harassment allegations have all served as grounds for event-driven cla=
ims of securities fraud supposedly tied to generalized statements.=C2=A0Lik=
e those briefs,=C2=A0I suggested that this case might be a chance for the S=
upreme Court to reconsider the growing idea that everything is securities f=
raud.Well, never mind. The Supreme Court decided the case yesterday and it =
is the most boring imaginable decision. If you were looking for the Supreme=
 Court to say =E2=80=9Cyou know what, not everything should be securities f=
raud,=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cyou know what, actually everything should be sec=
urities fraud,=E2=80=9D you will be disappointed. The decision is about a m=
inor technicality, sending the case back to an appeals court to think a bit=
 harder about whether Goldman=E2=80=99s generic statements of honesty and i=
ntegrity inflated its stock price before the crisis.[3]The rule (from previ=
ous Supreme Court cases) is basically that Goldman can defeat the lawsuit b=
y showing that its statements =E2=80=9Cdid not actually affect the market p=
rice of the stock.=E2=80=9D The court of appeals concluded that Goldman did=
 not do that, but the=C2=A0Supreme Court wants that court to try again. The=
 court =E2=80=9C=E2=80=98should be open to all probative evidence on that q=
uestion=E2=80=94qualitative as well as quantitative=E2=80=94aided by a good=
 dose of common sense,=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D says the Supreme Court, helpfully.=
 Goldman had argued to the Supreme Court that the statements at issue here =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0about integrity, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0are so generic that the=
y could not possibly have affected the price; the Supreme Court basically s=
aid, well, no, it depends. =E2=80=9CAs a rule=C2=A0of thumb, =E2=80=98a mor=
e-general statement will affect a security=E2=80=99s price less than a more=
-specific statement on the same question.=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D Ah.Here=E2=80=
=99s a good passage (citations omitted):The generic nature of a misrepresen=
tation often will be important evidence of a lack of price impact, particul=
arly in cases proceeding under the inflation-maintenance theory. Under that=
 theory, price impact is the amount of price inflation maintained by an all=
eged misrepresentation=E2=80=94in other words, the amount that the stock=E2=
=80=99s price would have fallen =E2=80=9Cwithout the false statement.=E2=80=
=9D Plaintiffs typically try to prove the amount of inflation indirectly: T=
hey point to a negative disclosure about a company and an associated drop i=
n its stock price; allege that the disclosure corrected an earlier misrepre=
sentation; and then claim that the price drop is equal to the amount of inf=
lation maintained by the earlier misrepresentation.But that final inference=
=E2=80=94that the back-end price drop equals front-end inflation=E2=80=94st=
arts to break down when there is a mismatch between the contents of the mis=
representation and the corrective disclosure. That may occur when the earli=
er misrepresentation is generic (e.g., =E2=80=9Cwe have faith in our busine=
ss model=E2=80=9D) and the later corrective disclosure is specific (e.g., =
=E2=80=9Cour fourth quarter earnings did not meet expectations=E2=80=9D). U=
nder those circumstances, it is less likely that the specific disclosure ac=
tually corrected the generic misrepresentation, which means that there is l=
ess reason to infer front-end price inflation=E2=80=94that is, price impact=
=E2=80=94from the back-end price drop.The plaintiffs=E2=80=99 theory here i=
s that Goldman=E2=80=99s stock price was too high because it kept talking a=
bout how much integrity it had, and the proof is that, when the news came o=
ut that it had less integrity, the stock price dropped. But that is not=C2=
=A0quite how a normal person would describe=C2=A0what happened. What happen=
ed is not that Goldman went around saying =E2=80=9Cour clients=E2=80=99 int=
erests always come first=E2=80=9D and then one day it said =E2=80=9Cwe=E2=
=80=99ve done an audit and actually our clients=E2=80=99 interests usually =
come fourth=E2=80=9D and the stock dropped. What happened is that Goldman w=
ent around saying =E2=80=9Cour clients=E2=80=99 interests always come first=
=E2=80=9D and then a global financial crisis occurred in part =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0in very small part =E2=80=94=C2=A0because Goldman=E2=80=99s clients=E2=
=80=99 interests did not always come first. And then Goldman=E2=80=99s stoc=
k dropped. Does that mean that Goldman=E2=80=99s stock was too high because=
 Goldman was lying about its clients=E2=80=99 interests always coming first=
?How=E2=80=99s GameStop doing?A classic problem in corporate finance is tha=
t companies often sell stock when times are tough and they need money, and =
they usually buy back stock when times are good and they have plenty=C2=A0o=
f money. This makes sense from a=C2=A0corporate finance perspective=C2=A0(s=
elling stock gets you money to do projects; buying back stock uses the mone=
y you get from the projects and rewards shareholders for funding them), but=
 is generally bad from a price perspective. If you need money because times=
 are tough, you will probably be selling stock at a low price: Who wants to=
 invest in a company that is running out of money? If you are buying back s=
tock because times are good, you will probably be buying stock at a high pr=
ice: The high stable profits that fund your buyback also make the stock mor=
e valuable.So there is a general sense that, when companies trade their own=
 stock, they tend to buy high and sell low. That sounds like bad trading. Y=
ou are supposed to buy low and sell high. Arguably this is the wrong way to=
 think about it, though. Arguably companies should be proud of selling low =
and buying high. Arguably their loyalty ought to be to their shareholders; =
if the company sells low and buys high that means that its counterparties =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0the shareholders =E2=80=94=C2=A0are doing well. If a company=
 is too good at timing its stock sales and repurchases =E2=80=94=C2=A0if it=
=E2=80=99s constantly selling stock at peaks and buying it back at troughs =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0then it is making money for shareholders at the expense of, =
you know, shareholders.[4]Anyway the whole dynamic seems to have reversed w=
ith meme stocks. GameStop Corp.,  the greatest of the meme stocks, was a ma=
ll-based video-game retailer that has transformed in the last few months in=
to some sort of tech-company rocket-ship abstraction. The thing about selli=
ng video games in malls is that it produces steady cash flows (until a glob=
al pandemic hits) but is in secular decline, which means (1) money comes in=
, (2) you have nothing better to spend it on than stock buybacks and (3) th=
e stock is cheap. So here=E2=80=99s a sentence from GameStop=E2=80=99s most=
 recent 10-K:In aggregate, during fiscal 2019, we repurchased a total of 38=
.1 million shares of our Class A Common Stock, totaling $198.7 million, for=
 an average price of $5.19 per share.On the other hand, the thing about bei=
ng a vague tech-company rocket-ship abstraction is that it requires a lot o=
f cash (to figure out what that actually means and then implement it) and p=
eople love it, which means (1) you need money, (2) you can get it by sellin=
g stock, and (3) the stock will be expensive. So here=E2=80=99s a GameStop =
press release this morning:GameStop Corp. (NYSE: GME) (=E2=80=9CGameStop=E2=
=80=9D or the =E2=80=9CCompany=E2=80=9D) today announced that it has comple=
ted its previously announced =E2=80=9Cat-the-market=E2=80=9D equity offerin=
g program (the =E2=80=9CATM Offering=E2=80=9D).GameStop disclosed on June 9=
, 2021 that it filed a prospectus supplement with the U.S. Securities and E=
xchange Commission to offer and sell up to a maximum of 5,000,000 shares of=
 its common stock from time to time through the ATM Offering. The Company u=
ltimately sold 5,000,000 shares of common stock and generated aggregate gro=
ss proceeds before commissions and offering expenses of approximately $1,12=
6,000,000.It is hard not to admire this. They bought 38.1 million shares tw=
o years ago=C2=A0at $5.19 each; they sold 5 million shares in the last two =
weeks at $225.20 each. GameStop is up 33.1 million shares=C2=A0and=C2=A0$92=
7 million on these two trades. It bought so low and sold so high. It=E2=80=
=99s a great trade and I congratulate GameStop. But, you know, don=E2=80=99=
t do it too often.=E2=80=9CDon=E2=80=99t do it too often,=E2=80=9D I say, a=
nd yet I cannot help myself. What if the GameStop meme run=C2=A0does=C2=A0e=
nd? What if the transformation to a tech company never goes anywhere? What =
if it consumes only a fraction of that $1.1 billion (which will be used =E2=
=80=9Cfor general corporate purposes as well as for investing in growth ini=
tiatives and maintaining a strong balance sheet=E2=80=9D)? What if, a year =
from now, GameStop is trading at $20=C2=A0it has a billion dollars of cash =
on its balance sheet? If you ran GameStop, wouldn=E2=80=99t you be a little=
 tempted to pivot back to buying back stock?


