<td class=3D"body-component__content" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; m=
so-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt; line-height: 150%; padding: 0 =
10px;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Everything might be=C2=A0securities fraud</h2><p style=3D"margin: 16p=
x 0;">We <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24222441.=
253607/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDIt=
MDMvZ29sZG1hbi1zYWNocy1nb2VzLXRvLXN1cHJlbWUtY291cnQtaGVkZ2UtZnVuZHMtd29uLW9=
uLWdhbWVzdG9wLWtrcG9lNndz/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB32a2494d" itemprop=3D"St=
oryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> talked in February</a> =
about a securities-fraud lawsuit against Goldman Sachs Group Inc. that was =
going all the way to the=C2=A0Supreme Court. The issue is that, before the =
2008 global financial crisis, Goldman had gone around saying things like =
=E2=80=9Cour clients=E2=80=99 interests always come first=E2=80=9D and =E2=
=80=9Cintegrity and honesty are at the heart of our business.=E2=80=9D Then=
 the global financial crisis occurred, and:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type=
: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bott=
om: 5px;">It came out that maybe Goldman=E2=80=99s clients=E2=80=99 interes=
ts sometimes came second, and maybe integrity and honesty were sometimes no=
t quite at the=C2=A0<em>heart=C2=A0</em>of its business[1]; and</li>=09<li =
style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Goldman=E2=80=99s stock price went down.</li>=
</ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Why did the stock price go down? Well, I =
mean, there=C2=A0<em>was=C2=A0</em>a global financial crisis. That was bad,=
 for earnings and such. Also, though,=C2=A0Goldman got in (legal, political=
, public-relations) trouble for some of the specific instances in which its=
 clients=E2=80=99 interests arguably came second; for instance, famously, i=
t <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24222441.253607/=
aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9uZXdzL3ByZXNzLzIwMTAvMjAxMC0xMjMuaHRt/607f07ceef=
4b8524a319a23cB90aa87b2" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" sty=
le=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width=
: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background=
-color: #ccc;">paid a big fine</a> for doing some bad=C2=A0stuff with a mor=
tgage security called Abacus.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There i=
s perhaps a third, less specific reason. Perhaps in 2007, investors read in=
 Goldman=E2=80=99s disclosures that=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cour clients=E2=80=99 inte=
rests always come first=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cintegrity and honesty are at =
the heart of our business,=E2=80=9D and they thought: =E2=80=9CYes, it is g=
ood that Goldman has integrity and puts its clients=E2=80=99 interests firs=
t, that is valuable for its business, we will buy the stock.=E2=80=9D In 20=
09, after Abacus and so forth, investors thought =E2=80=9Calas, no, Goldman=
 does not have integrity and does not put its clients=E2=80=99 interests fi=
rst, we are disappointed, we will sell the stock.=E2=80=9D In other words, =
perhaps investors=C2=A0<em>ascribed value=C2=A0</em>to Goldman=E2=80=99s st=
atements about integrity and honesty, and then when they found out that tho=
se statements were not true that value went away and the stock went down.</=
p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Are you laughing? A little, right? Investors=
 mainly ascribed value to Goldman=E2=80=99s income stream, and the stock ma=
inly went down due to Goldman losing money. But of course,=C2=A0at some mar=
gin integrity is valuable, and maybe investors thought Goldman had like 100=
 units of integrity (after reading their disclosures) but revised that esti=
mate down to 80 units (after reading the Abacus settlement), and each unit =
of integrity was worth a dollar to the stock price and so forth.</p><p styl=
e=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you believe this theory, then it was=C2=A0<em>secu=
rities fraud=C2=A0</em>for Goldman to talk a lot about having a lot of inte=
grity and honestly when in fact it secretly knew that it had less integrity=
 and honesty. Goldman was cooking the integrity-and-honesty books. Each qua=
rter the results came in and the business delivered only 80 units of honest=
y and integrity, but the market was demanding 100 units, so Goldman=E2=80=
=99s executives fudged the numbers and reported a full supply of honesty an=
d integrity. =E2=80=9COur clients=E2=80=99 interests came first on 73 out o=
f 91 days this quarter,=E2=80=9D the assistant treasurer reported, and the =
chief financial officer was like =E2=80=9Cthat=E2=80=99s not good enough, w=
e need to report that our clients=E2=80=99 interests=C2=A0<em>always=C2=A0<=
/em>came first, find a way to make it happen!=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margi=
n: 16px 0;">Anyway this went to the Supreme Court and there were some argum=
ents about the theory=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0which I talk about a lot around h=
ere =E2=80=94=C2=A0that =E2=80=9Ceverything is securities fraud.=E2=80=9D I=
f companies say vague nice things about themselves =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9C=
we have a code of ethics,=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9Cthe client comes first,=E2=80=
=9D =E2=80=9Cwe have a culture of risk management,=E2=80=9D etc. =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0and then a bad thing happens, a shareholder will sue, arguing that th=
e vague nice statements were <em>lies=C2=A0</em>that deceived investors and=
 pumped up the stock, and that when the bad thing happened the truth was re=
vealed and the stock dropped. When we <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomber=
gbusiness.com/click/24222441.253607/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGl=
uaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDItMDMvZ29sZG1hbi1zYWNocy1nb2VzLXRvLXN1cHJlbWUtY2=
91cnQtaGVkZ2UtZnVuZHMtd29uLW9uLWdhbWVzdG9wLWtrcG9lNndz/607f07ceef4b8524a319=
a23cC32a2494d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"colo=
r: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bor=
der-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #c=
cc;"> talked about it in February</a>, I quoted some <em>amicus curiae</em>=
 briefs like this one[2]:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Frequ=
ently, event-driven claims allege that generic or aspirational statements, =
similar to ones made by virtually every public company, maintained inflatio=
n in a company=E2=80=99s stock price. Allegations of wrongdoing nearly alwa=
ys conflict, at some level of generality, with a company=E2=80=99s code of =
conduct or other statements of corporate policy. So it is not difficult for=
 plaintiffs to allege that negative reporting or disclosures =E2=80=9Ccorre=
cted=E2=80=9D a prior, generic policy statement (e.g., =E2=80=9CWe strive t=
o comply with all applicable laws.=E2=80=9D). The result is that just about=
 any corporate controversy that coincides with a drop in stock price can be=
 re-characterized as a securities fraud. Examples abound. COVID-19 exposure=
 on cruise ships, wildfires, data breaches, and sexual-harassment allegatio=
ns have all served as grounds for event-driven claims of securities fraud s=
upposedly tied to generalized statements.=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D=
"margin: 16px 0;">Like those briefs,=C2=A0I suggested that this case might =
be a chance for the Supreme Court to reconsider the growing idea that every=
thing is securities fraud.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Well, never mind=
. The Supreme Court decided the case yesterday and it is the <a href=3D"htt=
ps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24222441.253607/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cu=
c3VwcmVtZWNvdXJ0Lmdvdi9vcGluaW9ucy8yMHBkZi8yMC0yMjJfMmM4My5wZGY/607f07ceef4=
b8524a319a23cBd016d55f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" styl=
e=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width:=
 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-=
color: #ccc;">most boring imaginable decision</a>. If you were looking for =
the Supreme Court to say =E2=80=9Cyou know what, not everything should be s=
ecurities fraud,=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cyou know what, actually everything sh=
ould be securities fraud,=E2=80=9D you will be disappointed. The decision i=
s about a minor technicality, sending the case back to an appeals court to =
think a bit harder about whether Goldman=E2=80=99s generic statements of ho=
nesty and integrity inflated its stock price before the crisis.[3]</p><p st=
yle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The rule (from previous Supreme Court cases) is bas=
ically that Goldman can defeat the lawsuit by showing that its statements =
=E2=80=9Cdid not actually affect the market price of the stock.=E2=80=9D Th=
e court of appeals concluded that Goldman did not do that, but the=C2=A0Sup=
reme Court wants that court to try again. The court =E2=80=9C=E2=80=98shoul=
d be open to all probative evidence on that question=E2=80=94qualitative as=
 well as quantitative=E2=80=94aided by a good dose of common sense,=E2=80=
=99=E2=80=9D says the Supreme Court, helpfully. Goldman had argued to the S=
upreme Court that the statements at issue here =E2=80=94=C2=A0about integri=
ty, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0are so generic that they could not possibly have af=
fected the price; the Supreme Court basically said, well, no, it depends. =
=E2=80=9CAs a rule=C2=A0of thumb, =E2=80=98a more-general statement will af=
fect a security=E2=80=99s price less than a more-specific statement on the =
same question.=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D Ah.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here=
=E2=80=99s a good passage (citations omitted):</p><blockquote><p style=3D"m=
argin: 16px 0;">The generic nature of a misrepresentation often will be imp=
ortant evidence of a lack of price impact, particularly in cases proceeding=
 under the inflation-maintenance theory. Under that theory, price impact is=
 the amount of price inflation maintained by an alleged misrepresentation=
=E2=80=94in other words, the amount that the stock=E2=80=99s price would ha=
ve fallen =E2=80=9Cwithout the false statement.=E2=80=9D Plaintiffs typical=
ly try to prove the amount of inflation indirectly: They point to a negativ=
e disclosure about a company and an associated drop in its stock price; all=
ege that the disclosure corrected an earlier misrepresentation; and then cl=
aim that the price drop is equal to the amount of inflation maintained by t=
he earlier misrepresentation.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But that fina=
l inference=E2=80=94that the back-end price drop equals front-end inflation=
=E2=80=94starts to break down when there is a mismatch between the contents=
 of the misrepresentation and the corrective disclosure. That may occur whe=
n the earlier misrepresentation is generic (e.g., =E2=80=9Cwe have faith in=
 our business model=E2=80=9D) and the later corrective disclosure is specif=
ic (e.g., =E2=80=9Cour fourth quarter earnings did not meet expectations=E2=
=80=9D). Under those circumstances, it is less likely that the specific dis=
closure actually corrected the generic misrepresentation, which means that =
there is less reason to infer front-end price inflation=E2=80=94that is, pr=
ice impact=E2=80=94from the back-end price drop.</p></blockquote><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The plaintiffs=E2=80=99 theory here is that Goldman=E2=
=80=99s stock price was too high because it kept talking about how much int=
egrity it had, and the proof is that, when the news came out that it had le=
ss integrity, the stock price dropped. But that is not=C2=A0<em>quite </em>=
how a normal person would describe=C2=A0what happened. What happened is not=
 that Goldman went around saying =E2=80=9Cour clients=E2=80=99 interests al=
ways come first=E2=80=9D and then one day it said =E2=80=9Cwe=E2=80=99ve do=
ne an audit and actually our clients=E2=80=99 interests usually come fourth=
=E2=80=9D and the stock dropped. What happened is that Goldman went around =
saying =E2=80=9Cour clients=E2=80=99 interests always come first=E2=80=9D a=
nd then a global financial crisis occurred in part =E2=80=94=C2=A0in very s=
mall part =E2=80=94=C2=A0because Goldman=E2=80=99s clients=E2=80=99 interes=
ts did not always come first. And then Goldman=E2=80=99s stock dropped. Doe=
s that mean that Goldman=E2=80=99s stock was too high because Goldman was l=
ying about its clients=E2=80=99 interests always coming first?</p><h2 style=
=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial, Helveti=
ca, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bottom-width:=
 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px 5px;">How=
=E2=80=99s GameStop doing?</h2><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A classic probl=
em in corporate finance is that companies often sell stock when times are t=
ough and they need money, and they usually buy back stock when times are go=
od and they have plenty=C2=A0of money. This makes sense from a=C2=A0corpora=
te finance perspective=C2=A0(selling stock gets you money to do projects; b=
uying back stock uses the money you get from the projects and rewards share=
holders for funding them), but is generally bad from a price perspective. I=
f you need money because times are tough, you will probably be selling stoc=
k at a low price: Who wants to invest in a company that is running out of m=
oney? If you are buying back stock because times are good, you will probabl=
y be buying stock at a high price: The high stable profits that fund your b=
uyback also make the stock more valuable.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">S=
o there is a general sense that, when companies trade their own stock, they=
 tend to buy high and sell low. That sounds like bad trading. You are suppo=
sed to buy low and sell high. Arguably this is the wrong way to think about=
 it, though. Arguably companies should be proud of selling low and buying h=
igh. Arguably their loyalty ought to be to their shareholders; if the compa=
ny sells low and buys high that means that its counterparties =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0the shareholders =E2=80=94=C2=A0are doing well. If a company is too good=
 at timing its stock sales and repurchases =E2=80=94=C2=A0if it=E2=80=99s c=
onstantly selling stock at peaks and buying it back at troughs =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0then it is making money for shareholders at the expense of, you know, sh=
areholders.[4]</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway the whole dynamic see=
ms to have reversed with meme stocks. GameStop Corp., <a href=3D"https://li=
nk.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24222441.253607/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21=
iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDEtMjUvdGhlLWdhbWUtbmV2ZXItc3RvcH=
M/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB4d0a46e1" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"it=
emscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-=
bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid=
; background-color: #ccc;"> the greatest of the meme stocks</a>, was a mall=
-based video-game retailer that has transformed in the last few months into=
 some sort of tech-company rocket-ship abstraction. The thing about selling=
 video games in malls is that it produces steady cash flows (until a global=
 pandemic hits) but is in secular decline, which means (1) money comes in, =
(2) you have nothing better to spend it on than stock buybacks and (3) the =
stock is cheap. So here=E2=80=99s a sentence from GameStop=E2=80=99s <a hre=
f=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24222441.253607/aHR0cHM6=
Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9peD9kb2M9L0FyY2hpdmVzL2VkZ2FyL2RhdGEvMTMyNjM4MC8wMDAxMzI=
2MzgwMjEwMDAwMzIvZ21lLTIwMjEwMTMwLmh0bQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB5bcae498" =
itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; tex=
t-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-colo=
r: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">most recen=
t 10-K</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In aggregate, durin=
g fiscal 2019, we repurchased a total of 38.1 million shares of our Class A=
 Common Stock, totaling $198.7 million, for an average price of $5.19 per s=
hare.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On the other hand, the t=
hing about being a vague tech-company rocket-ship abstraction is that it re=
quires a lot of cash (to figure out what that actually means and then imple=
ment it) and people love it, which means (1) you need money, (2) you can ge=
t it by selling stock, and (3) the stock will be expensive. So here=E2=80=
=99s a <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24222441.25=
3607/aHR0cHM6Ly9pbnZlc3Rvci5nYW1lc3RvcC5jb20vbmV3cy1yZWxlYXNlcy9uZXdzLXJlbG=
Vhc2UtZGV0YWlscy9nYW1lc3RvcC1jb21wbGV0ZXMtbWFya2V0LWVxdWl0eS1vZmZlcmluZy1wc=
m9ncmFtLTA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB198bcd57" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsc=
ope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important=
; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-sty=
le: solid; background-color: #ccc;">GameStop press release this morning</a>=
:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">GameStop Corp. (NYSE: GME) (=
=E2=80=9CGameStop=E2=80=9D or the =E2=80=9CCompany=E2=80=9D) today announce=
d that it has completed its previously announced =E2=80=9Cat-the-market=E2=
=80=9D equity offering program (the =E2=80=9CATM Offering=E2=80=9D).</p><p =
style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">GameStop disclosed on June 9, 2021 that it filed =
a prospectus supplement with the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission to=
 offer and sell up to a maximum of 5,000,000 shares of its common stock fro=
m time to time through the ATM Offering. The Company ultimately sold 5,000,=
000 shares of common stock and generated aggregate gross proceeds before co=
mmissions and offering expenses of approximately $1,126,000,000.</p></block=
quote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It is hard not to admire this. They boug=
ht 38.1 million shares two years ago=C2=A0at $5.19 each; they sold 5 millio=
n shares in the last two weeks at $225.20 each. GameStop is up 33.1 million=
 shares=C2=A0<em>and=C2=A0</em>$927 million on these two trades. It bought =
so low and sold so high. It=E2=80=99s a great trade and I congratulate Game=
Stop. But, you know, don=E2=80=99t do it too often.</p><p style=3D"margin: =
16px 0;">=E2=80=9CDon=E2=80=99t do it too often,=E2=80=9D I say, and yet I =
cannot help myself. What if the GameStop meme run=C2=A0<em>does=C2=A0</em>e=
nd? What if the transformation to a tech company never goes anywhere? What =
if it consumes only a fraction of that $1.1 billion (which will be used =E2=
=80=9Cfor general corporate purposes as well as for investing in growth ini=
tiatives and maintaining a strong balance sheet=E2=80=9D)? What if, a year =
from now, GameStop is trading at $20=C2=A0it has a billion dollars of cash =
on its balance sheet? If you ran GameStop, wouldn=E2=80=99t you be a little=
 tempted to pivot back to buying back stock?</p>
