5px;">VOTE</h2><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One type of investing business =
is an activist hedge fund. You buy concentrated stakes in a handful of comp=
anies after careful analysis, and then use proxy fights, meetings and stron=
gly worded letters to try to influence those companies=E2=80=99 behavior. I=
f you succeed, they make changes to their business and their stocks go up. =
You charge your investors a lot of money for this service.</p><p style=3D"m=
argin: 16px 0;">Another type of investing business is a passive index fund.=
 You buy stock in every company indiscriminately. The stocks go up because =
stocks mostly go up, not because you picked good ones; you are aiming for t=
he market return, not outperformance. You charge your investors as little a=
s possible =E2=80=94=C2=A0a few basis points, maybe zero =E2=80=94=C2=A0for=
 this service.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">These are sort of opposite b=
usiness models but they have important=C2=A0synergies. If you run an activi=
st hedge fund, much of your work is about trying to get other big sharehold=
ers to support your activist campaigns: They have a lot of votes, and if th=
ey vote for you then. you will win your proxy fights. It turns out that the=
 biggest investors are often index funds. So if you are an activist who is =
friends with the index funds, that is good for business.</p><p style=3D"mar=
gin: 16px 0;">Meanwhile if you run a passive index fund, you will sometimes=
 become annoyed with the managers of your portfolio companies and want them=
 to make changes to their business. You might own a lot of shares and have =
a lot of votes, but your influence will be somewhat muted by your passivity=
. You can=E2=80=99t threaten to sell the stock if the managers don=E2=80=99=
t do what you want. You are temperamentally unlikely to do a proxy fight yo=
urself. But if some sympathetic activist could light a fire under the manag=
ers, that would be helpful.[5] (The phrase is =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://l=
